  "next_recommended_step": "M5j: wire the validated bulk persistent read-alignment backend behind a graph-facing dry-run consumption seam, preserving oracle diff gates before any graph mutation.",
  "plain_language_assessment": {
    "measured_advantage": "On the M5h 3546-fixture toy-hifi harvest, bulk persistent CUDA averaged 0.302834 ms versus CPU 0.333798 ms before TSV/JSON emission, a 1.102x hot-path speedup.",
    "what_improved": "Changing persistent CUDA output transfer from thousands of tiny per-fixture copies to one bulk copy per shape group removed the dominant device-to-host overhead.",
    "what_it_does_not_claim": "This is not an end-to-end Flye speedup and does not yet mutate Flye graph state; it proves a bounded read-alignment chain replay backend can beat CPU before TSV/JSON emission while preserving oracle output.",
    "why_it_matters": "This is the first read-alignment replay batch where CUDA is faster for the measured bounded pre-write hot path, not just faster inside the kernel."
  },
